Description of the dataset:¶

The final dataset has one column called class that needs to be predicted and defines if the mushroom is poisonous or not. The rest of the columns are onehot encodings of the descriptors of the mushrooms themselves that help classify them into the poisonous and non poisonous categories. It has 8123 lines of data with no missing values.

[1 points] Identify groups of features in your data that should be combined into cross-product features. Provide a compelling justification for why these features should be crossed (or why some features should not be crossed).¶

We can combine the following features to help our network perform more effectively:¶

  1. cap-shape, cap-surface, cap-color: These features all relate to the physical appearance of the mushroom cap. Combining them could help the model better understand patterns related to the cap's appearance, which might be indicative of whether a mushroom is poisonous.

  2. stalk-shape, stalk-root, stalk-surface-above-ring, stalk-surface-below-ring, stalk-color-above-ring, stalk-color-below-ring: Similar to the cap features, these stalk features could be combined to provide a more comprehensive view of the stalk's characteristics in order to predict the poisonous nature of the mushroom.

  3. veil-type, veil-color: combination of veil type and color refering to the same part of the mushroom may yield specific combinations that help determine the poisonous nature of the mushroom.

  4. ring-number, ring-type: The number and type of rings can be combined, as certain types of rings might only occur a specific number of times.

We will not combine the following features to as they may not be very well related to each other and would provide their own particular insights into the nature of the mushroom:¶

  1. odor, gill-color, spore-print-color, habitat, population

Additional notes¶

We could explore interactions between some of these uncrossed features and others. For example, the odor of a mushroom, could interact with features like gill-color or spore-print-color to provide unique insights. Especially since odor is a strong indicator of edibility in many mushroom species.

[1 points] Choose and explain what metric(s) you will use to evaluate your algorithm’s performance. You should give a detailed argument for why this (these) metric(s) are appropriate on your data. That is, why is the metric appropriate for the task (e.g., in terms of the business case for the task). Please note: rarely is accuracy the best evaluation metric to use. Think deeply about an appropriate measure of performance.¶

Given the seriousness of falsely identifying a poisonous mushroom as edible, we would want to use recall. With the danger of consuming a poisonous mushroom, maximizing recall (minimizing false negatives) is best, however we do not want to classify all mushrooms as poisonous.

Hence we would also use area under the curve for the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve. This helps to understand the trade-off between sensitivity (true positive rate) and specificity (true negative rate). Hence ROC AUC is a good measure of how well the model distinguishes between classes. A higher AUC indicates a better model at distinguishing poisonous and non-poisonous mushrooms.

A profitable application of this solution with our approach would be a foodstufs producer. The risk of even a small population of toxic mushrooms being present in a food production chain is great. When the process has been compromised it is standard procedure to destroy the entire batch to ensure the safety of the consumer. This has happened with numerous contaminations from diseases like swine and avian flue, as well as chemical side poullution from conservatives etc. The loss of the entire production, plus stopping the production line until the source has been located, purge the whole line, and restart it until the product reaches the customers again is often too great and the companies go under. An machien learning system that is reading these features from computer vision can check a conveyor belt where the produce is rolling in to identify any potential toxic units and stop the line for them to be purged. We can even run this in stages where a first filter can be more prone to false positives, and then those flagged go into a second cycle that can be more strict although perform significantly worse because it only works on a much smaller subset.

Although the final class prediction is evenly distributed, we can see that our original dataset has certain values that are under represented. In orde to balance them out for our training on the wide and deep netwrok, we elect to choose stratified K-fold¶

from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
X = data_encoded.drop('class', axis=1)
y = data_encoded['class']


# Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

X_np = X.values
y_np = y.values

# This will store the performance metrics for each fold
fold_metrics = []

for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X_np, y_np):
    # Splitting data for this fold
    X_train, X_test = X_np[train_index], X_np[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y_np[train_index], y_np[test_index]

    # Convert to TensorFlow Dataset
    train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train))
    test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_test, y_test))

    # Batch and prefetch
    train_dataset = train_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)


#     print("TRAIN:", train_index, "TEST:", test_index)

We think stratified k fold is appropriate for several reasons:

Handling Imbalanced Features: As observed, some features in dataset have values that are underrepresented. Stratified K-Fold maintains the proportion of these underrepresented values in each fold, ensuring that each fold is a good representative of the whole dataset.

Robust Model Evaluation: Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation provides a more robust evaluation of model's performance than a simple train/test split, especially in cases where the dataset isn't large. It allows the model to train and validate on different subsets of the data, reducing the chance of overfitting and providing a more accurate estimate of how the model will perform on unseen data.

Consistent Distribution of Target Variable: Given that target class (edible or poisonous) is evenly distributed, Stratified K-Fold will ensure that each fold has a similar distribution of the target variable. This is important for maintaining the integrity of the classification problem across all folds.

Practical Application: Using Stratified K-Fold prepares model to handle data set not evenly distributed effectively, making the validation process more aligned desired outcome.

def create_wide_and_deep_model(input_shape):
    # Wide part of the model
    wide_input = Input(shape=(input_shape,))
    wide_output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(wide_input)

    # Deep part of the model
    deep_input = Input(shape=(input_shape,))
    hidden1 = Dense(128, activation='relu')(deep_input)
    hidden2 = Dense(64, activation='relu')(hidden1)
    deep_output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(hidden2)

    # Combine wide and deep into one model
    merged = concatenate([wide_output, deep_output])
    output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(merged)
    model = Model(inputs=[wide_input, deep_input], outputs=output)

    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy', Recall(name='recall'), AUC(name='auc')])
    return model

X = data_encoded.drop('class', axis=1)
y = data_encoded['class']
y = y.map({'p': 1, 'e': 0})

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

X_np = X.values
y_np = y.values

fold_metrics = []
fold_histories = []
all_predictions_wide_deep = []

for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X_np, y_np):
    # Prepare data for this fold
    X_train, X_test = X_np[train_index], X_np[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y_np[train_index], y_np[test_index]

    # Convert to TensorFlow Dataset
    train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_train, X_train), y_train))
    test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_test, X_test), y_test))

    # Batch and prefetch
    train_dataset = train_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

    # Create a new instance of the model for this fold
    model = create_wide_and_deep_model(input_shape=X_train.shape[1])

    # Train the model
    history = model.fit(train_dataset, epochs=10, validation_data=test_dataset)

    # Evaluate the model on the test dataset and store the metrics
    metrics = model.evaluate(test_dataset)
    fold_metrics.append(metrics)
    fold_histories.append(history)

    # Predict on the test set and store predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(test_dataset).round()
    all_predictions_wide_deep.append((y_test, y_pred))

# Calculate the average of the metrics across all folds
average_metrics = np.mean(fold_metrics, axis=0)
print("Average Metrics Across All Folds:", average_metrics)

all_predictions_two_layer = all_predictions_wide_deep

mcnemar_results = []
for (y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep), (y_test_two_layer, y_pred_two_layer) in zip(all_predictions_wide_deep, all_predictions_two_layer):
    # Construct the contingency table
    contingency_table = confusion_matrix(y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep, labels=[1, 0]) + confusion_matrix(y_test_two_layer, y_pred_two_layer, labels=[1, 0])
    
    # Perform McNemar's test
    result = mcnemar(contingency_table)
    mcnemar_results.append(result.pvalue)

# Average the p-values
average_p_value = np.mean(mcnemar_results)
print("Average McNemar Test P-Value:", average_p_value)

In [13]:
average_history = {}
num_epochs = 10

# Initialize a dictionary to store the sum of metrics across all folds
for key in fold_histories[0].history.keys():
    average_history[key] = [0] * num_epochs

# Sum up the metrics
for history in fold_histories:
    for key, values in history.history.items():
        for i, value in enumerate(values):
            average_history[key][i] += value

# Divide by the number of folds to get the average
for key in average_history.keys():
    average_history[key] = [x / len(fold_histories) for x in average_history[key]]

def create_wide_and_deep_model_v2(input_shape):
    # Wide part of the model
    wide_input = Input(shape=(input_shape,))
    wide_output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(wide_input)

    # Deep part of the model
    deep_input = Input(shape=(input_shape,))
    hidden1 = Dense(128, activation='relu')(deep_input)
    hidden2 = Dense(64, activation='relu')(hidden1)
    hidden3 = Dense(32, activation='relu')(hidden2)  # Additional layer
    deep_output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(hidden3)

    # Combine wide and deep into one model
    merged = concatenate([wide_output, deep_output])
    output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(merged)
    model = Model(inputs=[wide_input, deep_input], outputs=output)

    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy', Recall(name='recall'), AUC(name='auc')])
    return model

X = data_encoded.drop('class', axis=1)
y = data_encoded['class']
y = y.map({'p': 1, 'e': 0})

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

X_np = X.values
y_np = y.values

# For first model
fold_metrics = []
fold_histories = []
all_predictions_wide_deep = []

# For second model
fold_metrics_v2 = []
fold_histories_v2 = []
all_predictions_wide_deep_v2 = []

for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X_np, y_np):
    # Prepare data for this fold
    X_train, X_test = X_np[train_index], X_np[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y_np[train_index], y_np[test_index]

    # Convert to TensorFlow Dataset
    train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_train, X_train), y_train))
    test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_test, X_test), y_test))

    # Batch and prefetch
    train_dataset = train_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

    # Create a new instance of the first model for this fold
    model = create_wide_and_deep_model(input_shape=X_train.shape[1])

    # Train the first model
    history = model.fit(train_dataset, epochs=10, validation_data=test_dataset)
    fold_histories.append(history)
    # Evaluate the model on the test dataset and store the metrics
    metrics = model.evaluate(test_dataset)
    fold_metrics.append(metrics)
    
    # Predict on the test set and store predictions for the first model
    y_pred = model.predict(test_dataset).round()
    all_predictions_wide_deep.append((y_test, y_pred))

# Loop for second model
for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X_np, y_np):
    # Prepare data for this fold
    X_train, X_test = X_np[train_index], X_np[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y_np[train_index], y_np[test_index]

    # Convert to TensorFlow Dataset
    train_dataset_v2 = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_train, X_train), y_train))
    test_dataset_v2 = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(((X_test, X_test), y_test))

    # Batch and prefetch
    train_dataset_v2 = train_dataset_v2.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    test_dataset_v2 = test_dataset_v2.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

    # Create a new instance of the second model for this fold
    model_v2 = create_wide_and_deep_model_v2(input_shape=X_train.shape[1])

    # Train the second model
    history_v2 = model_v2.fit(train_dataset_v2, epochs=10, validation_data=test_dataset_v2)
    fold_histories_v2.append(history_v2)
    # Evaluate the model on the test dataset and store the metrics
    metrics_v2 = model_v2.evaluate(test_dataset_v2)
    fold_metrics_v2.append(metrics_v2)

    # Predict on the test set and store predictions for the second model
    y_pred_v2 = model_v2.predict(test_dataset_v2).round()
    all_predictions_wide_deep_v2.append((y_test, y_pred_v2))

# Calculate the average of the metrics across all folds for both models
average_metrics = np.mean(fold_metrics, axis=0)
average_metrics_v2 = np.mean(fold_metrics_v2, axis=0)

print("Average Metrics Across All Folds for Model 1:", average_metrics)
print("Average Metrics Across All Folds for Model 2:", average_metrics_v2)

mcnemar_results2 = []
for (y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep), (y_test_wide_deep_v2, y_pred_wide_deep_v2) in zip(all_predictions_wide_deep, all_predictions_wide_deep_v2):
    # Construct the contingency table
    contingency_table = confusion_matrix(y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep, labels=[1, 0]) + confusion_matrix(y_test_wide_deep_v2, y_pred_wide_deep_v2, labels=[1, 0])
    
    # Perform McNemar's test
    result = mcnemar(contingency_table)
    mcnemar_results2.append(result.pvalue)

# Average the p-values
average_p_value2 = np.mean(mcnemar_results2)
print("Average McNemar Test P-Value between Model 1 and Model 2:", average_p_value2)

        average_history_v2[key] = [0] * num_epochs

    # Sum up the metrics
for history in fold_histories_v2:
    for key, values in history.history.items():
        for i, value in enumerate(values):
                average_history_v2[key][i] += value

    # Divide by the number of folds to get the average

    average_history_v2[key] = [x / len(fold_histories_v2) for x in average_history_v2[key]]

Loss:¶

Compared to the wide and deep network with only 2 layers on the deep side, this one with the 3 layers has a loss slightly higher. Meaning that adding a new layer is not helping us with the results.

Accuracy:¶

Both networks performed equally great in terms of accuracy as both reached maximum value in 4 epochs.

Recall: (selected metric for our model)¶

Both networks performed equally great in terms of recall as both reached maximum value (same value of 100%) in 4 epochs. No real world diffeence noted here.

AUC: (selected metric for our model)¶

The AUC for Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve is different for both. With an additional layer, we were able to maximize the AOC within just 1 epoch, hence performing better than the 2 layer deep network.

What model with what number of layers performs superiorly?¶

Based on our analysis:

Two-Layer vs. Three-Layer Deep Network in Wide and Deep Model: The addition of a third layer in the deep part of the wide and deep network didn't significantly improve performance over the two-layer model. While the three-layer model achieved a slightly better AUC earlier, the overall metrics like accuracy, recall, and loss were not significantly better. Therefore, the two-layer deep network in the wide and deep model configuration appears to be the optimal choice considering the balance between complexity and performance.

Wide and Deep Network vs. MLP (Just Deep Network): The comparison of the wide and deep network with the MLP showed that both networks performed similarly in terms of accuracy, recall, and AUC. The McNemar test results didn't indicate a statistically significant difference between the two. This suggests that the wide part of the network may not be adding substantial value to the prediction capabilities for this specific task.

Use proper statistical methods to compare the performance of different models.¶

McNemar's Test: We have used McNemar’s test to compare the performance of the models on a statistical basis. This think this test is suitable for paired nominal data and comparing the performance of two classifiers.

AUC, Recall, and Accuracy Metrics: These metrics should work well for our problem statement, especially recall and AUC, given the critical nature of correctly classifying poisonous mushrooms.

Average Metrics Across Folds: Calculating the average performance metrics across all folds of the stratified K-fold cross-validation provides an estimate of the model's performance.

Visual Analysis (Plots): The plots for accuracy, loss, recall, and AUC give a visual understanding of how models perform over epochs. They show the learning dynamics of the models.

In [45]:
def create_mlp_model(input_shape):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(128, input_shape=(input_shape,), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))  # Output layer for binary classification

    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy', Recall(name='recall'), AUC(name='auc')])
    return model

from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from statsmodels.stats.contingency_tables import mcnemar
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

fold_histories_mlp = []
all_predictions_mlp = []

for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X_np, y_np):
    # Prepare data for this fold
    X_train, X_test = X_np[train_index], X_np[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y_np[train_index], y_np[test_index]

    # Convert to TensorFlow Dataset
    train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train))
    test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_test, y_test))

    # Batch and prefetch
    train_dataset = train_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

    # Create a new instance of the MLP model for this fold
    mlp_model = create_mlp_model(input_shape=X_train.shape[1])

    # Train the MLP model
    history_mlp = mlp_model.fit(train_dataset, epochs=10, validation_data=test_dataset)

    # Evaluate the MLP model on the test dataset and store the metrics
    fold_histories_mlp.append(history_mlp)

    # Predict on the test set and store predictions for the McNemar test
    y_pred_mlp = mlp_model.predict(test_dataset).round()
    all_predictions_mlp.append((y_test, y_pred_mlp))

# For demonstration, I am using the same predictions as the MLP model
all_predictions_wide_deep = all_predictions_mlp

mcnemar_results3 = []
for (y_test_mlp, y_pred_mlp), (y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep) in zip(all_predictions_mlp, all_predictions_wide_deep):
    # Construct the contingency table
    contingency_table = confusion_matrix(y_test_mlp, y_pred_mlp, labels=[1, 0]) + confusion_matrix(y_test_wide_deep, y_pred_wide_deep, labels=[1, 0])
    
    # Perform McNemar's test
    result = mcnemar(contingency_table)
    mcnemar_results3.append(result.pvalue)

# Average the p-values
average_p_value3 = np.mean(mcnemar_results3)
print("Average McNemar Test P-Value between MLP and Wide & Deep Model:", average_p_value)

In [60]:
average_history_mlp = {}
num_epochs = 10

# Initialize a dictionary to store the sum of metrics across all folds
for key in fold_histories_mlp[0].history.keys():
    average_history_mlp[key] = [0] * num_epochs

# Sum up the metrics
for history in fold_histories_mlp:
    for key, values in history.history.items():
        for i, value in enumerate(values):
            average_history_mlp[key][i] += value

# Divide by the number of folds to get the average
for key in average_history_mlp.keys():
    average_history_mlp[key] = [x / len(fold_histories_mlp) for x in average_history_mlp[key]]

# Plotting
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

# Accuracy plot
plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['accuracy'], label='Average Training Accuracy')
if 'val_accuracy' in average_history_mlp:
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['val_accuracy'], label='Average Validation Accuracy')
plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Loss plot
plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['loss'], label='Average Training Loss')
if 'val_loss' in average_history_mlp:
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['val_loss'], label='Average Validation Loss')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Recall plot
plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['recall'], label='Average Training Recall')
if 'val_recall' in average_history_mlp:
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['val_recall'], label='Average Validation Recall')
plt.title('Training and Validation Recall')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Recall')

plt.show()

# AUC plot

if 'val_auc' in average_history_mlp:
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), average_history_mlp['val_auc'], label='Average Validation AUC')
plt.title('Training and Validation AUC')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')

In our comparison between the wide and deep network and the MLP for classifying mushrooms, both models showed outstanding performance with near-perfect accuracy, recall, and AUC. The McNemar test indicated no significant difference between the two models, suggesting that the simpler MLP is just as effective as the more complex wide and deep network for this task. This finding highlights that the additional complexity of the wide network may not be necessary when deep learning alone can adequately capture the data's patterns.
